Buana Listya, Harum Energy, Jaya Agra: Indonesia Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-05-30T02:03:40Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-30/buana-listya-harum-energy-jaya-agra-indonesia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  gained 0.5 percent to 3,832.38.  Coal producers: Power-station coal  prices  at  Australia ’s
Newcastle port, an Asian benchmark, rose 2.3 percent to $119.47
a metric ton in the week ended May 27, according to the
 globalCOAL NEWC Index .  PT Bumi Resources (BUMI IJ),  Asia ’s biggest exporter of
power-station coal, advanced 0.8 percent to 3,375 rupiah and PT
Adaro Energy (ADRO IJ), Indonesia’s second-largest coal
producer, climbed 1.1 percent to 2,400 rupiah.  PT Bumi Resources Minerals (BRMS IJ): The company’s first-
quarter net income declined to 138.5 billion rupiah ($16.2
million) from 271.3 billion rupiah a year earlier as gold and
copper production at its affiliate PT Newmont Nusa Tenggara
dropped, the Indonesian mining company said in an e-mailed
statement in Jakarta. Bumi Resources Minerals fell 1.4 percent
to 700 rupiah.  PT Buana Listya Tama (BULL IJ): The company’s first-quarter
net income rose to 85.17 billion rupiah from 38.94 billion
rupiah a year earlier, it said in a statement published in
Investor Daily today. Buana Listya, the freight transportation
unit of  Indonesia ’s biggest shipping company PT Berlian Laju
Tanker (BLTA IJ), gained 1.8 percent to 168 rupiah. Berlian Laju
Tanker rose 1.4 percent to 375 rupiah.  PT Harum Energy (HRUM IJ): PT Karunia Bara Perkasa is
seeking to raise up to $301 million from a stock sale in the
Indonesian coal producer, according to a term sheet sent to
investors. Karunia Bara is offering 270 million Harum Energy
shares at 9,050 to 9,550 rupiah each, the terms show. Harum
Energy gained 3.2 percent to 9,550 rupiah.  PT Jaya Agra Wattie (JAWA IJ): The producer of rubber,
coffee and palm oil will start trading today after raising 566.2
billion rupiah from selling 1.13 billion new shares in an
initial public offering last week. The company plans to invest
1.5 trillion rupiah to increase plantation lands over the next
five years, Investor Daily reported, citing President Director
Harijadi Soedarjo.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  